Hoverflies are remarkable insects capable of hovering in mid-air, a feat that has inspired engineers to develop micro-air vehicles (MAVs) with similar capabilities \cite{mawson2012hoverfly}. One unique feature of hoverflies is their long, antenna-like structures called whiskers. However, the role of whiskers in hoverfly aerodynamics remains unclear. This study aims to fill this gap by examining the impact of whisker length on the aerodynamic performance of hoverflies.

